        <h2 id="what-is">What is MarketMuse?</h2>
        <p>MarketMuse is a content intelligence platform that uses proprietary topic modelling to analyse topical authority, identify content gaps, and generate research-backed briefs. Founded by Aki Balogh and Jeff Coyle, it sits upstream of every other content tool: it tells you <em>what</em> to write before tools like Surfer or Clearscope score <em>how</em> you wrote it.</p>

        <p>The core thesis: most content teams publish reactively — chasing keywords one at a time. MarketMuse maps the full competitive landscape, then recommends which topics to cover, in what order, to build authority systematically.</p>

        <p>The product does four things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Topic Authority</strong> — proprietary score for how comprehensively your domain covers a subject</li>
          <li><strong>Content Inventory</strong> — auditing every page on your site for topical coverage</li>
          <li><strong>AI Briefs</strong> — the most detailed content briefs in the category</li>
          <li><strong>First Draft</strong> — outline-driven AI drafting (still needs editing)</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What MarketMuse is <em>not</em>: a writer, a publisher, or a SERP-based scoring tool like Surfer.</p>

        <h2 id="features">MarketMuse features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Topic Authority — the headline metric</h3>
        <p>Enter any subject. MarketMuse returns your domain's Topic Authority score and benchmarks it against competitors. The score combines breadth, depth, and quality of coverage across all related subtopics — not just keyword presence. Higher scores correlate with higher rankings across the entire topic cluster.</p>

        <h3>2. Content Inventory — site-wide audit</h3>
        <p>Audits every page on your site, classifies each by topic, and surfaces gaps: subjects you cover thinly, competitor topics you ignore, and pages where your authority is leaking due to thin or off-topic content.</p>

        <h3>3. AI Briefs — the deliverable</h3>
        <p>This is what writers want. Each brief includes: target word count, recommended H2/H3 structure, semantically related entities to cover, suggested questions to answer, internal-link recommendations, and an authority target score. Significantly deeper than briefs from Frase or Surfer.</p>

        <h3>4. First Draft — outline-driven AI</h3>
        <p>Generates a structured AI draft from a brief. Output is more coherent than raw GPT-4 because the brief constrains it, but still needs editing. Most teams use First Draft as a starting point, not as the final article.</p>

        <h3>5. Competitive Content Analysis</h3>
        <p>Map your topical authority against any competitor in seconds. Useful for board reporting and for prioritising content investment — but the depth comes at a steep learning curve.</p>

